# API Client Layer

## Separation of Concerns

- **No UI logic in API layer** - pure data fetching only
- Keep API functions focused on HTTP communication
- Extract to service/API layer for reusability
- Document complex API calls with JSDoc comments

## Return Types

- Always return typed data (no `any`)
- Define proper TypeScript interfaces for API responses
- Use consistent response formats across all endpoints
- Handle errors appropriately and return meaningful error messages

## Error Handling

- Use consistent error format across all API calls
- Throw proper errors with context
- Don't expose sensitive information in error messages
- Log errors appropriately (client vs server)

## Example Pattern

```typescript
// features/students/api/students.ts

import type { Student, StudentCreateInput } from '../types'

export async function fetchStudents(): Promise<Student[]> {
  const response = await fetch('/api/students')
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error(`Failed to fetch students: ${response.statusText}`)
  }
  return response.json()
}

export async function createStudent(data: StudentCreateInput): Promise<Student> {
  const response = await fetch('/api/students', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify(data),
  })
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error(`Failed to create student: ${response.statusText}`)
  }
  return response.json()
}
```

## Data Mappers

- Use mapper functions to transform data
- Keep raw API responses separate from UI data structures
- Transform data at the boundary (API → Domain)
- Document transformation logic
